.ezboard.com/uestopidiera.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Estopidiera</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Registered User</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>8/29/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>2:46:59 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Enstill vs. Root  (little bit about wis/ac)</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">This is a long-discussed topic, and was reading on a previous discussion some advice to people under 34 not to buy or use enstill.<br>
<br>
I think this is a little confusing to some people, and it certainly has been to me.<br>
<br>
But this has been my combat experience:<br>
<br>
1. Root works best to quickly stop a mob. It seems to be resisted less and can survive a nuke a bit better. Also takes less cast time (useful if the mob has resisted slow). For DoT's I notice no difference in break-rates. Your mileage may vary. Root lasts less time but sticks more. This is the biggest difference. You will NEVER be able to med up a bub of mana while a creature has only one root on. Don't expect it to be a &quot;I can get enough mana now to finish this guy off&quot; spell.<br>
<br>
2. Enstill has a longer cast time, and lasts longer. It is resisted more at all levels from what I can tell. Enstill is the spell of choice if you are without an enchanter and are just keeping a mob out of combat range of your group IMHO. Mobs not being nuked or dotted who are enstilled break free of it no more than mobs who are rooted from what I can tell.<br>
<br>
HOWEVER: When mobs are engaged in melee ... (read pet) ... they seem to break enstill less. And even when they are not, if Enstill holds you can quite often get a full bub of mana while doing the shaman dance after you get your pet off of them.<br>
<br>
So, when soloing, I use enstill. If it is resisted once or twice, Eh. That's why I have SoW and the mobs don't.<br>
<br>
Pull with Togor's. Run away from pet. Enstill. DoT with  whatever flavors you DoT with.<br>
<br>
Move a good run away from mob and med. If Enstill is on when E-Bolt or VoS has run its course, re-apply (this will often break Enstill ... so be ready to either re-Enstill or send pet). For most blue Kunark mobs this is all you need to do. Mobs with extra special high numbers of HP (which seems to be named mobs) will need more cycles of this at which point your base Wis will matter a lot.<br>
<br>
After mob is to 1/2 to 1/3 life left, apply pet with taunt on, sit and med some more. Watch pet health and mob health simultaneously using that &quot;/assist&quot; hotbutton you made. Heal pet only as a last resort, as this is a huge waste of mana.<br>
<br>
So ... to go back to AC/Wis debate. IMHO ... AC all the way for groups where you are not a healer. If you're in a group where you'll be casting those wicked DoT's get your AC up. I hardly ever get one ... most of the time people are so terrified of my DoT's causing corpse loss of mobs or breaking mezzes etc that I get scolded about imagining I could use one. (/em wonders if warriors are told not to use their swords because they can break mezzes.) With Cannibalize you hardly ever go into battle with full HP anyway, so get the AC. But if you solo ... Wis wis wis. Our solo style is so different from our group style that it justifies having two entirely different sets of gear ...<br>
<br>
Now if I could only afford them ...<br>
<br>
Estopidiera McTiernan<br>
Shamaness of Halas, Officer of The Shadow Order<br>
